<p class=""><h2>Key Challenges in the Surgical Camera System Market</h2><ul>    <li><strong>High Cost of Equipment:</strong> The initial investment for advanced surgical camera systems can be prohibitively high, limiting accessibility for smaller hospitals and clinics.</li>    <li><strong>Integration Issues:</strong> Many surgical camera systems struggle with compatibility and integration with existing operating room infrastructure, leading to inefficiencies in surgical workflows.</li>    <li><strong>Technological Complexity:</strong> Rapid advancements in technology mean that surgical teams must constantly adapt to new systems, increasing the need for training and ongoing education.</li>    <li><strong>Regulatory Hurdles:</strong> Compliance with stringent regulations can delay the market entry of innovative surgical camera technologies, ultimately hindering growth.</li>    <li><strong>Maintenance and Support:</strong> The high maintenance costs and the need for specialized technical support can deter healthcare providers from investing in new camera systems.</li></ul><h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Surgical Camera System Market</h2><ul>    <li><strong>Emerging Technologies:</strong> Innovations such as 4K and 3D imaging, along with augmented reality integration, present significant opportunities to enhance visualization during surgeries, fostering market growth.</li>    <li><strong>Telemedicine and Remote Surgery:</strong> The rise of telemedicine and robotic-assisted surgeries opens avenues for surgical cameras that support remote interventions, increasing demand across the healthcare sector.</li>    <li><strong>Miniaturization:</strong> Developing smaller, portable surgical camera systems can enhance their utility in minimally invasive procedures, catering to a rising trend in outpatient surgeries.</li>    <li><strong>AI Integration:</strong> Embedding artificial intelligence capabilities for real-time image analysis and decision support can improve di